{"id":"1106.1163","submitter":"Changbiao Wang","authors":"Changbiao Wang","title":"Plane wave in a moving medium and resolution of the Abraham-Minkowski\n  debate by the special principle of relativity","comments":"(1) Abstract and Sec. V were revised to highlight research results\n  obtained; (2) Attachment-V was removed. 25 pages, 3 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, a novel approach for resolution of the Abraham-Minkowski\ndebate is proposed, in which the principle of relativity is used to uniquely\ndetermine the light momentum formulation for a plane wave in a moving\nnon-dispersive lossless isotropic uniform medium. It is shown by analysis of\nthe plane-wave solution that, (1) there may be a pseudo-power flow when a\nmedium moves, and the Poynting vector does not necessarily denote the direction\nof real power flowing, (2) Minkowski's light momentum and energy constitute a\nLorentz four-vector in a form of single photon or single EM-field cell, and\nPlanck constant is a Lorentz invariant, (3) there is no momentum transfer\ntaking place between the plane wave and the uniform medium, and the EM momentum\nconservation equation cannot be uniquely determined without resort to the\nprinciple of relativity, and (4) the moving medium behaves as a so-called\n\"negative index medium\" when it moves opposite to the wave vector at a\nfaster-than-dielectric light speed. It is also shown by analysis of EM-field\nLorentz transformations that, when a static electric (magnetic) field moves in\nfree space, neither Abraham's nor Minkowski's formulation can correctly\ndescribe a real electromagnetic momentum; as an application of this principle,\nthe classical electron mass-energy paradox is analyzed and resolved. Finally, a\ngeneral EM momentum definition is proposed, and according to this new\ndefinition, the traditional \"Abraham-type\" and \"Minkowski-type\" momentums in\nthe dispersion wave-guiding systems, such as regular dielectric-filled metallic\nwaveguides, are found to be included in the same momentum formulation, but they\nappear at different frequencies.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 6 Jun 2011 19:47:45 GMT"},{"version":"v10","created":"Wed, 13 Jul 2011 10:30:36 GMT"},{"version":"v11","created":"Thu, 14 Jul 2011 10:39:32 GMT"},{"version":"v12","created":"Mon, 18 Jul 2011 18:05:28 GMT"},{"version":"v13","created":"Tue, 19 Jul 2011 19:31:21 GMT"},{"version":"v14","created":"Mon, 25 Jul 2011 19:41:23 GMT"},{"version":"v15","created":"Thu, 28 Jul 2011 08:02:56 GMT"},{"version":"v16","created":"Sun, 31 Jul 2011 22:19:29 GMT"},{"version":"v17","created":"Mon, 8 Aug 2011 02:03:10 GMT"},{"version":"v18","created":"Wed, 10 Aug 2011 08:53:04 GMT"},{"version":"v19","created":"Fri, 12 Aug 2011 10:35:06 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 9 Jun 2011 19:44:19 GMT"},{"version":"v20","created":"Thu, 18 Aug 2011 10:47:17 GMT"},{"version":"v21","created":"Sun, 11 Sep 2011 08:40:15 GMT"},{"version":"v22","created":"Sat, 24 Sep 2011 16:47:16 GMT"},{"version":"v23","created":"Tue, 11 Oct 2011 09:31:43 GMT"},{"version":"v24","created":"Thu, 13 Oct 2011 17:26:13 GMT"},{"version":"v25","created":"Mon, 17 Oct 2011 05:55:29 GMT"},{"version":"v26","created":"Tue, 25 Oct 2011 21:13:52 GMT"},{"version":"v27","created":"Thu, 3 Nov 2011 03:13:55 GMT"},{"version":"v28","created":"Mon, 28 Nov 2011 19:47:57 GMT"},{"version":"v29","created":"Wed, 30 Nov 2011 11:45:11 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 14 Jun 2011 19:07:35 GMT"},{"version":"v30","created":"Tue, 6 Dec 2011 11:25:05 GMT"},{"version":"v31","created":"Thu, 29 Dec 2011 02:56:53 GMT"},{"version":"v32","created":"Wed, 4 Jan 2012 06:04:01 GMT"},{"version":"v33","created":"Tue, 17 Jan 2012 08:13:30 GMT"},{"version":"v34","created":"Mon, 23 Jan 2012 09:03:49 GMT"},{"version":"v35","created":"Mon, 20 Feb 2012 08:28:11 GMT"},{"version":"v36","cre