{"id":"1106.1225","submitter":"Berengere Dubrulle","authors":"Berengere Dubrulle","title":"Anomalous scaling and generic structure function in turbulence","comments":null,"journal-ref":"J. Phys II France vol 6 p 1825-1840 (1996)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn cond-mat.other nlin.CD","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We discuss on an example a general mechanism of apparition of anomalous\nscaling in scale invariant systems via zero modes of a scale invariant\noperator. We discuss the relevance of such mechanism in turbulence, and point\nout a peculiarity of turbulent flows, due to the existence of both forcing and\ndissipation. Following these considerations, we show that if this mechanism of\nanomalous scaling is operating in turbulence, the structure functions can be\nconstructed by simple symmetry considerations. We find that the generical scale\nbehavior of structure functions in the inertial range is not self-similar\n$S_n(\\ell)\\propto \\ell^{\\zeta_n}$ but includes an \"exponential self-similar\"\nbehavior $S_n(\\ell) \\propto \\exp[\\zeta_n\\alpha^{-1} \\ell^{\\alpha}]$ where\n$\\alpha$ is a parameter proportional to the inverse of the logarithm of the\nReynolds number. The solution also follows exact General Scaling and\napproximate Extended Self-Similarity.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 7 Jun 2011 00:50:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2011-06-08"}
